               <msContents>
                  <summary>The first of three volumes of poetical English translations from Persian
                     by British poet, orientalist, and painter, <persName role="aut trl scr"
                        key="person_55689478" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/55689478">Charles Fox
                        (1749–1809)</persName>, together with <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6853"><idno>Persian MS
                           356</idno></ref> and <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6854">357</ref>. After
                     his death, his friend <persName>Rev. Adam Clarke (1762–1832)</persName>
                     apparently obtained disparate notes by Fox and had them uniformly bound up as a
                     set. Many entries contain references to the manuscripts that Fox studied with
                     occasional dates. This volume contains metrical English translations of ghazals
                     by the poet <persName>Ḥāfiẓ</persName>.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_355-item1">
                     <author role="trl" key="person_55689478">
                        <persName xml:lang="en" type="supplied">Fox, Charles 1749–1809</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="desc" key="work_6850">Persian Translations</title>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="alt" key="work_6850">Poetical translations from the
                        Persian by the late C. Fox, Esq., of Bristol</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="" type="beginning"> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a"
                           >1a</locus>: MS no. 4 Hafiz:<lb/> چون تیغ اجل زند سیر‌ها هیچ است<lb/>
                        When Destiny Unsheaths the Sword of Death... </incipit>

                     <explicit xml:lang="ar">Folio <locus from="126a" to="126a">126a</locus>: Hafiz:
                        Ms No. 3<lb/> در سنبل آوتخیم از روی نیاز<lb/> In the sweet Hyacinthien
                        Hair...<lb/> To die in raptures of delight<lb/> preludes the gloom of
                        Fortune's night. </explicit>
                     <colophon>No colophon.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="en" otherLangs="fa">English and Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
